{"id":"1809.10269","submitter":"Majid Mirzanezhad","authors":"Mees van de Kerkhof, Irina Kostitsyna, Maarten L\\\"offler, Majid\n  Mirzanezhad and Carola Wenk","title":"Global Curve Simplification","comments":"33 pages, 16 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Due to its many applications, \\emph{curve simplification} is a long-studied\nproblem in computational geometry and adjacent disciplines, such as graphics,\ngeographical information science, etc. Given a polygonal curve $P$ with $n$\nvertices, the goal is to find another polygonal curve $P'$ with a smaller\nnumber of vertices such that $P'$ is sufficiently similar to $P$. Quality\nguarantees of a simplification are usually given in a \\emph{local} sense,\nbounding the distance between a shortcut and its corresponding section of the\ncurve. In this work, we aim to provide a systematic overview of curve\nsimplification problems under \\emph{global} distance measures that bound the\ndistance between $P$ and $P'$. We consider six different curve distance\nmeasures: three variants of the \\emph{Hausdorff} distance and three variants of\nthe \\emph{Fr\\'echet} distance. And we study different restrictions on the\nchoice of vertices for $P'$. We provide polynomial-time algorithms for some\nvariants of the global curve simplification problem and show NP-hardness for\nother variants. Through this systematic study we observe, for the first time,\nsome surprising patterns, and suggest directions for future research in this\nimportant area.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 26 Sep 2018 23:46:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 22 Jan 2020 16:06:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-23"}
